\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
6.
 Policy Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.1 Media Access and Storage
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Personnel shall store physical and digital media containing Confidential or Restricted information (including CJI) within physically secure locations or locked containers when not in active use.
 Media shall only be accessible to authorized personnel with a validated business need-to-know.
 Removable digital media shall be encrypted using FIPS-validated cryptographic modules (FIPS 140-3,
 or FIPS 140-2 until September 21,
 2026) prior to storing any Level 3 (Confidential) or Level 4 (Restricted) data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.2 Media Marking and Labeling
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Where technically feasible,
 personnel shall mark or label physical media and removable digital media containing Confidential or Restricted data with the assigned classification level.
 This control ensures personnel remain aware of the required handling and disclosure constraints.
 Labels shall omit system-specific or operational details that could increase the risk of targeted theft.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.3 Media Transport
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Personnel shall transport media containing Confidential or Restricted data using continuous chain-of-custody controls.
 Digital media in transit must employ FIPS-validated cryptographic modules (FIPS 140-3,
 or FIPS 140-2 until September 21,
 2026).
 If physical media containing Restricted data (e.g.,
 printed CJI) must be transported outside of a physically secure location,
 it shall remain under the direct,
 continuous physical control of authorized personnel or be shipped via a tracked courier service utilizing signature verification upon delivery.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.4 Digital Media Sanitization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Information Operations personnel shall sanitize all digital media prior to disposal,
 release,
 external transfer,
 lease return,
 or internal reuse.
 Sanitization must execute methods (Clear,
 Purge,
 or Destroy) strictly consistent with NIST SP 800-88 Rev.
 1 guidelines,
 subject to the stricter CJIS requirements defined herein.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Clear
\series default
:
 Acceptable only for the internal reuse of media that solely stored Level 1 (Public) or Level 2 (Internal Use) data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Purge
\series default
:
 Mandatory for the internal reuse of media that previously stored Level 3 (Confidential) or Level 4 (Restricted) non-CJI data.
 Cryptographic Erase (CE) constitutes an acceptable purge method for non-CJI data if the storage device natively supports it and utilizes FIPS-validated encryption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
CJIS Overwrite Requirement
\series default
:
 Media that stores or has stored Criminal Justice Information (CJI) shall be overwritten at least three (3) times or degaussed prior to disposal or release to unauthorized individuals.
 CE shall not be used for CJI media unless explicit,
 written approval is obtained from the CJIS Systems Officer (CSO).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Destroy
\series default
:
 Mandatory for End-of-Life (EOL) digital media or any media that cannot be successfully purged or overwritten.
 Destruction shall render the data permanently irretrievable and the media physically unusable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Networking Equipment
\series default
:
 Networking equipment NVRAM shall be sanitized utilizing vendor-approved factory-reset commands or physical destruction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Equipment Testing
\series default
:
 Information Operations personnel shall test sanitization equipment and procedures annually to verify that the intended sanitization is achieved.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.5 Physical Media Sanitization and Destruction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Personnel shall destroy physical media (e.g.,
 paper documents) containing Confidential or Restricted data when no longer required,
 executing a method that renders the information unrecoverable (e.g.,
 cross-cut shredding or incineration).
 The destruction of physical media containing Personally Identifiable Information (PII) shall strictly comply with the destruction standards mandated by NRS 603A.210.
 Personnel shall not place intact physical media containing sensitive data into standard waste or recycling receptacles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.6 Records of Sanitization,
 Disposal,
 and Verification
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Information Operations shall comprehensively document and verify all sanitization and disposal actions for IT-managed assets.
 Required documentation shall include the date of sanitization,
 the unique Asset Identifier (Tag ID),
 the specific sanitization method utilized,
 the final disposition of the media,
 the identity of the personnel executing the sanitization,
 and the identity of the personnel performing the post-sanitization verification.
 For media that stores or has stored Criminal Justice Information (CJI),
 the post-sanitization verification shall be performed by a secondary,
 independent Information Operations staff member who did not execute the initial sanitization (Dual Authorization).
 Verification shall consist of a documented test read or visual inspection to confirm the sanitization was effective.
 Electronic waste (E-Waste) transferred to approved third-party recycling vendors shall mandate an official Certificate of Destruction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.7 Prohibited Media Types
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The use of personally owned removable media (e.g.,
 personal USB flash drives,
 external hard drives) on Elko County information systems is strictly prohibited.
 Only County-procured,
 encrypted portable storage devices that are actively cataloged within the CMDB shall be authorized for use.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.8 Multifunction Printers (MFPs) and Copier Handling
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Elko County utilizes MFPs with internal storage drives capable of caching Confidential and Restricted data.
 The terminal disposition of these assets is subject to strict chain-of-custody and sanitization controls.
 Specific MFP models and their corresponding configuration limitations shall be documented within the CMDB and supporting Standard Operating Procedures (SOPs).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Automated Data Removal Limitations
\series default
:
 Information Operations personnel shall configure MFPs to execute automated job data removal no less than weekly and shall implement automated alerting for job data removal failures.
 In the event of an automated job data removal failure,
 Information Operations personnel shall execute a manual clearing within twenty-four (24) hours of the alert.
 Personnel must acknowledge that automated job data removal operates solely as a defense-in-depth risk mitigation and does not constitute terminal sanitization for CJI media.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Contractual "Keep Your Drive" Requirement
\series default
:
 All MFP lease or purchase agreements executed after the effective date of this policy shall incorporate a "Keep Your Drive" provision.
 At lease expiration or hardware replacement,
 Elko County shall remove and retain the internal storage media for physical destruction in accordance with Section 6.5.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
On-Site Vendor Sanitization
\series default
:
 For pre-existing lease agreements executed prior to the effective date of this policy that lack a "Keep Your Drive" provision,
 the vendor shall not remove the asset from Elko County facilities until a CJIS-compliant three-pass overwrite or degauss has been executed on-site.
 Information Operations personnel shall visually verify the overwrite or degauss and obtain a Certificate of Sanitization prior to the hardware's departure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Inoperable Media (Break/Fix)
\series default
:
 Vendor technicians shall not remove inoperable MFP drives that cannot be logically overwritten.
 Elko County shall classify these drives as physical media for destruction and shall retain them regardless of warranty or lease return requirements.
 The IT Director shall proactively notify vendors of this requirement in writing prior to any service event to ensure compliance at the time of a break/fix call.
\end_layout

